postcontent: LMT provided a CQB MRP Defender Model 16 for testing. This rifle uses their CQB MRP Monolithic receiver/forend. The forend includes two flush-cup sling attachments on either side and one on the bottom. The rails are all mil-spec, numbered, and completely SOPMOD compatible. The overall diameter is narrow, allowing for the addition of protective rails that do not make it overly large. Two Torx screws are used to attach the barrel. The rifle came with a set of LMT removable A2-type sights. The barrel is 16 inches long, chrome-lined and cryogenically treated with a 1-in-7-inch twist rate. The bolt carrier group is a standard semi-auto group with a standard charging handle. A torque wrench and driver are included to make certain the barrel tensioning screws are not over-tightened. The upper is mated to a Defender 2000 lower receiver, which contains a mil-spec single-stage trigger that is crisp and solid. The rifle ships with one 30-round magazine, two heavy-duty push-button sling swivels, three rail panels and a tactical sling. The buttstock is an LMT SOPMOD model with battery compartments on either side. Swapping out barrels on the MRP is really easy. Simply unscrew and remove the two screws and it pulls right out. It has the side benefit of making cleaning really easy. Swap the barrels and tighten the screws using the torque wrench. The manual calls for 140-inch-pounds of torque tightened front to back. The trick here is not to over-tighten them—you really do not need to crank them down. By using the same setting each time, it generally makes for little change in point of impact with a barrel change and your receiver will last forever.

title: For Sale:  Reloading Setup
postcontent: Get started reloading today and save big money on ammunition costs. Load custom ammunition for hunting or inexpensive ammunition for the range. The kit includes the Lee Challenger Press, the Lee Ram Prime, the Lee Auto Disk Powder Measure, the Pro Upgrade Kit, the Double Disk Upgrade Kit, and Adjustable Charge Bar for the Powder Measure.This is all you need to get started in reloading, except for a die set (you will need components including cases, bullets, reloading powder, and primers however).These items are in excellent to nearly new condition.Here's more information about these items: Lee Challenger Press - can handle everything from the smallest pistol to the largest rifle calibers. It features a steel ram and operating linkage, a very strong "O" frame that is larger than the average press opening giving reloaders maximum hand clearance. When de-priming, spent primers are sent directly into the trash can helping to keep reloading areas nice and clean. Lee Ram Prime - allows the reloader to prime on the up-stroke for a more sensitive feel and increased leverage. Included are easy to change punches for both large and small primers.Lee Auto-Disk Powder Measure - automatically dispense charges. The case itself actuates the measure as the neck is being flared. The measure is actuated during the presses maximum mechanical advantage. This assures the smooth, even action of the measure. Built-in baffle and precisely molded, glass reinforced charge disks contribute to the charge uniformity.Lee Auto-Disk Powder Measure Upgrade Kit - Upgrades the Lee Auto Disk to function like the Pro version and features a new round powder reservoir, an elastomer wipe, shut off valve, and swivel adapterDouble Disk Kit and Adjustable Charge Bar - These work with the Auto-Disk Powder measure and allow you to automatically measure and dispense (drop in reloading parlance) up to 28.8 grains of Unique and 42.2 grains of IMR 4064 (this kit will work with all brands of smokeless powder) by raising the powder hopper permitting two disks to be stacked in powder measure. It allows the user to double the capacity and make very fine adjustments by adjusting up or down in 1/10th grain increments using different combinations of disks. The charge bar has an adjustable cavity and allows even finer adjustment of powder drops for handgun cartridges

title: For Sale:  Hornady XTP Bullets 9mm (355 Diameter) 90 Grain Jacketed Hollow Point Box of 100
postcontent: 2 Boxes $15 eachHornady XTP bullets were designed for hunting, self-defense, and law enforcement. One of the great things about the XTP bullet is reliable performance, it features controlled expansion where six serrations divide the bullet into six symmetrical sections. These sections weaken the jacket to allow controlled expansion at low velocities and ensures fragmentation does not occur at high velocities. The XTP bullet is really known for its stopping power. They were designed from the beginning to expand reliably at a variety of handgun velocities and deliver deep, terminal penetration with every shot. Most handgun bullets are designed to perform at a single factory-specified velocity where the XTP bullet is designed to offer controlled expansion over a range of velocities. Each XTP Bullet has a swaged core and drawn copper jacket to ensure uniform expansion and in-flight stability. Adding a cannelure to this bullet keeps the core and the jacket locked together while also allowing the cartridge case to tightly crimp, adding security at high velocities. This is not loaded ammunition

title: For Sale:  Rock River Arms AR-15 DMR Build, 20" Stainless Bull Barrel, Bushnell Elite 3200 5-15x Scope
postcontent: I'd love to keep a hold of this firearm, but it's time for some late-season spring cleaning. Here is my AR-15 DMR, capable of sub-minute groups and equipped with a number of upgrades, including a scope, sling, and some upgraded Magpul furniture. Note: The bipod is not included! (I only have one and want to keep it).Upper Receiver Group: At the core of this rifle is a Predator Pursuit complete upper receiver by Rock River Arms, sporting a 20-inch stainless steel bull barrel chambered in .223 Wylde. This chambering accepts both 5.56 NATO and .223 Rem while maintaining better accuracy than a NATO chamber, and the barrel has a 1:8 twist to stabilize nearly any bullet you'd run through it. I used this rifle for a Precision Scoped Rifle Skill Builder course at the SIG Sauer Academy, and it shot consistent sub-MOA five-shot groups at 100 yards. Moving out to 200 yards, I managed to pull off a 1.5 and 1.6-inch group -- that's 0.75 and 0.8 MOA, respectively! At 300 yards, it was child's play to consistently hit a row of four-inch-diameter steel plates. This rifle can shoot.Lower Receiver Group: The lower is a complete unit from Surplus Ammo and Arms, with an upgraded match trigger and the trigger guard and pistol grip upgraded to Magpul furniture. The pistol grip is a modular Magpul MIAD, with a core that holds five spare rounds of ammunition. The trigger is a Rock River Arms Two-Stage Varmint Trigger. This is a lighter, crisper version of their excellent National Match trigger, and this unit is rated to break at 3.5 to four pounds of force, following a first-stage takeup. It is excellent for precision work.Optic: The optic here is a Bushnell Elite Tactical 3200 scope, with a 5-15x magnification range, parallax adjustment, and a mil-dot reticle. Adjustments are in increments of 1/4 MOA. I have this rifle zeroed spot-on at 100 yards for 75 grain HPBT match ammunition, and I also have scope adjustment data I can give you for both 75 grain match and 55 grain ball ammunition out to 300 yards (data gathered by me shooting in the field). The scope is clear, repeatable, and reliable, and has plenty of magnification for anywhere in the effective range of this rifle. The scope mount is nothing fancy -- I picked it up on eBay after I had spent all my money on the upper, lower, and optic. However, the mount has been 100% reliable, and held zero through many years of use.Sling: I'll include the high quality, padded sling I've been using with this rifle. Every rifle needs a good sling.Miscellaneous Notes: Weight -- with the 20" bull barrel, this is not a featherweight carbine. This is meant as a midrange DMR (designated marksman rifle)/varmint/predator rifle. It shines best when shot as such - from support or a bipod! If you haven't yet delved into the world of long range shooting, it's a blast. This rifle, and its affordable ammunition, can be a relatively inexpensive gateway into the sport. Magazines -- this rifle has had flawless reliablity with aluminum/steel magazines. For whatever reason, it occasionally fails to strip a round from my 20 round Gen 2 Magpul PMags. I would recommend that you run this rifle with metal magazines, and it will perform at its best.If interested, please shoot me a message! Upon purchase, I'll need to see two forms of ID; one being a New Hampshire driver's license. No out of state sales, please! Thanks for your interest.
